<div id="outline-container-org300eca2" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="org300eca2">Poetry Vocabulary</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-org300eca2">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-orgeed2096" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="orgeed2096">Elements</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-orgeed2096">
</div>
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="orgb4a1c43"></a>Stanza: a group of consecutive lines in a poem that form a single unit<br /></li>
<li><a id="orgc5feed7"></a>Meter: a regular pattern of stressed and unstressed syllables<br />
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="org93d2eb7"></a>˘ /   ˘    /   ˘      /   ˘   /   ˘ /   ˘    /   ˘    /  ˘ /<br /></li>
<li><a id="orgb9c57b6"></a>I do not like green eggs and ham, I do not like them Sam I am<br /></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a id="orgf3f1dc9"></a>Iambic pentameter: a line of poetry containing five beats: unstressed syllable then a stressed syllable<br />
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="org023dec7"></a>˘   /     ˘     /     ˘   /  ˘   /  ˘     /<br /></li>
<li><a id="orgc5762da"></a>But SOFT, what LIGHT from YONder WINdow BREAKS?<br /></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a id="orgcd679c1"></a>Rhyme: the repetition of accented vowel sounds following them in words that are close together in a poem (such as mean and screen). Not all poems rhyme.<br /></li>
<li><a id="orga6ab43f"></a>End Rhyme: rhymes at the end of lines of poetry<br />
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="orgd8b2a81"></a>The world would end tomorrow afternoon<br /></li>
<li><a id="orgb347d1a"></a>But short of that, it might be too soon<br /></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a id="org9d32d91"></a>Rhyme Scheme: the pattern of end rhymes in a poem<br />
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="org75e73e7"></a>Little Miss Muffet  a<br /></li>
<li><a id="org70d7be4"></a>Sat on a tuffet a<br /></li>
<li><a id="org8987f27"></a>Eating her curds and whey b<br /></li>
<li><a id="org3bc75ab"></a>Along came a spider c<br /></li>
<li><a id="org1571fff"></a>And sat down beside her c<br /></li>
<li><a id="orgf689e44"></a>And frightened Miss Muffet away b<br /></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a id="org276fc20"></a>Internal Rhyme: rhymes within lines of poetry<br />
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="orgab57c76"></a>Back in the chamber turning, all my soul within me burning.<br /></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a id="org3e650a5"></a>Approximate/Slant Rhyme: rhymes involving sounds that are similar but not exactly the same<br />
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="orgb4450a8"></a>(such as leave/live)<br /></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a id="orgb5f6b11"></a>Refrain: a repeated sound, word, phrase, line, or group of lines<br />
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="orgef80a2e"></a>“I gotta a feeling, that tonight’s gonna be a good night, that tonight’s gonna be a good night”<br /></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a id="orga83d05b"></a>Quatrain: four lined stanzas of any kind—rhymed, metered, etc.<br /></li>
<li><a id="orgc6e5a32"></a>Prose: any writing that is not poetry<br />
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="org34d1380"></a>(essays, novels, short stories, etc.)<br /></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a id="orgdbd3adf"></a>Couplet: two consecutive lines in a poem, usually rhyming<br />
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="org49a9f0d"></a>The outlook wasn’t brilliant for the Mudville nine that day;<br /></li>
<li><a id="org644982f"></a>The score stood four to two, with but one inning more to play;<br /></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a id="orgd432b11"></a>Onomatopoeia: the use of words whose sounds imitate or suggest their meaning<br />
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="org03b5e9c"></a>(buzz, rustle, boom, tick tock, crunch, sizzle)<br /></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a id="org2b7f7a3"></a>Speaker: the voice talking to us in the poem<br />
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="org22e2b94"></a>The voice is sometimes, but not always, the poet. Think of the <span class="underline"><span class="underline"><span class="underline"><span class="underline"><span class="underline"><span class="underline">__</span></span></span></span></span></span> (or the voice) as a character the author has created.<br /></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a id="org0309244"></a>Pun: a play on words, either on different senses of the same  word or on the similar sense or sound of different words<br /></li>
<li><a id="org2ac73ce"></a>Assonance: repeated vowel sounds in non-rhyming words<br />
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="orgb6749ef"></a>He was way late to pick the grapes in May.<br /></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a id="orgc7fe2a2"></a>Alliteration: the repetition of the same consonant sounds in words that are close together, or the repetition of consonant sounds that are very similar<br />
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="org98b1eea"></a>She stopped and stood still for a long time<br /></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org040e9fc" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org040e9fc">Types</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-org040e9fc">
</div>
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="orge3d8ab1"></a>Ode: a lyric poem, rhymed or unrhymed, that praises something or someone<br /></li>
<li><a id="orgcf19f43"></a>Narrative: a poem that tells a story<br /></li>
<li><a id="orgec97e72"></a>Free Verse: a poem that has no pattern of meter or regular rhyme scheme<br /></li>
<li><a id="org2b57a92"></a>Lyric Poem: a poem that expresses the feelings or thoughts of a speaker; It does NOT tell a story<br /></li>
<li><a id="orgd259997"></a>Ballad: a song or songlike poem that tells a story mostly dealing with adventure or romance<br /></li>
<li><a id="org6aa2d2f"></a>Elegy: a poem of mourning or grief, usually about someone who has died<br /></li>
<li><a id="org217fbc5"></a>Sonet: a fourteen-line poem, usually written in iambic pentameter.  Shakespeare wrote these with a specific rhyming scheme of:<br />
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="orgf57905b"></a>ABAB CDCD EFEF GG<br /></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a id="orgc9fa4ea"></a>Lymeric: a very short humorous or nonsensical poem with five lines and an AABBA rhyme scheme<br /></li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</div>
